postcontent:
http://extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=319

This is an incredibly accurate, full power 44 Mag., lead free load. The long-for-weight all copper bullet uses up the limited powder capacity of the case and keeps us from driving the bullet any faster than we are currently doing.

This 44 mag. load will work great and give adequate penetration for hunting big game species up to about 350 lbs. Since the bullet weight is relatively light, this load only generates moderate recoil.

At Buffalo Bore we always use real over-the-counter firearms to develop our published velocities. We believe the long time industry wide duplicitous practice of using extra long laboratory barrels to achieve exaggerated published velocities is unfair to the customer as he/she will never be able to duplicate such laboratory type velocities in the real world, where it matters. Note our real world velocities below.

1676 fps -- Marlin 1894, 18 inch barrel
1475 fps -- Ruger Super Blackhawk, 5.5 inch barrel
1399 fps -- S&W MT Gun, 4 inch barrel

title: For Sale:  Remington 710 in 30-06 with Vortex Crossfire 6-24x50mm Illuminated Mil-Dot Scope
postcontent:
I have for sale, a Remington model 710, chambered in 30-06 Springfield. I have owned it for 6 years. It is in good condition. It is sighted in for 100 yards at 0. It is EXTREMELY accurate. From what I hear about this particular model of rifle, I have one of the really good ones. I always hit what I am aiming at - you could drive nails at 350 yards with it. I consistently come away with a 1 inch group at 300 yards.

It is a bolt-action rifle, with a 4-round magazine. It is comfortable to shoot, and has a polymer stock, so its easy to hold onto even when its raining. Easy cleaning - flip up the bolt release lever and the bolt slides right out. The trigger pull is decent for an inexpensive hunting rifle.

The scope is a 50mm Vortex Crossfire, with 6-24x optical zoom, and illuminated mil-dots. Add a bi-pod to this rifle, and you'd have a great sniper rifle. The scope is fantastic, and, though it was already a VERY accurate rifle, has increased the accuracy dramatically. I took a picture of some trees through the scope, which are 1.32 miles away, and then took a picture of the same area outside the scope for perspective.

The scope has a lifetime replacement warranty - even if you drop it and break the lenses, they will replace it. Incredible optics.

I really don't want to sell this, but I need to. I have priced the whole package fairly, with rifle, scope, hard case, and 28 rounds of 30-06 (ranging from 165 to 180 grain, and standard jacketed rounds to soft-tip Core-Lokt rounds), at $500.

The PS90 is a carbine version of the P90, intended for civilian shooters for personal protection and sporting use; it was introduced in 2005, and continues to be offered in several configurations. 

The PS90 will accept the standard 50-round P90 magazines In order to be legal for purchase by civilians without obtaining a tax stamp for a Short Barreled Rifle (SBR) as defined by the United States National Firearms Act, the PS90 carbine has an extended 407 mm (16 in) barrel and is semi-automatic, with a trigger pull of approximately 31 to 36 N (7 to 8 lbF). The lengthened barrel has eight rifling grooves, with a right-hand twist rate of 1:229 mm (1:9 in) and a rifled length of 376 mm (14.8 in); the muzzle is equipped with a fixed "birdcage" type flash suppressor. Despite the added barrel length, the PS90 is relatively compact and lightweight, with an overall length of 667 mm (26.3 in), and a weight of 3.4 kg (7.5 lb) with a fully loaded 50-round magazine. Due to the added barrel length, the PS90 can also achieve a muzzle velocity of up to 777 m/s (2,550 ft/s) with SS195LF ammunition, or up to 930 m/s (3,050 ft/s) with third party ammunition.

title: For Sale:  Attention Collectors! 1903 Springfield - Excellent Condition
postcontent: I have a Rock Island 1903 Springfield, chambered in .30-06, that is in excellent condition. This is a true collector's item as this gun is in outstanding shape. All serials match on the various components from what I have been able to determine. This is in the safe to shoot range of serials and production records show that it is WWI to WWII era. The barrel is a National Match style from what I have been able to determine from research. Barrel rifling is in superb condition, with only very minor salt and peppering appropriate to the gun's age and overall appearance. The bolt and action are in superb appearance and function flawlessly. This is a seriously accurate shooter! The butt plate is in great condition, with only minor amounts of wear along the top edge from normal handling and use. There is no cleaning kit in the stock, but the gun does have the original sling that was first issued with the rifle. The stock shows no signs of cracking of other failure and the finish has very little surface wear. I have had this gun professionally appraised on numerous occassions and have been quoted values ranging from $1600 to $2200. I would like to sell it outright and am accepting offers, but am open to trades. No junk please. Only reasonable offers will be considered. More photos available on request.

title: For Sale:  WATCH OUT FOR SCAMMERS!
postcontent:
There are a bunch of scammer listings out in the last 48 hours.  If they don't have a city listed and the listing sale price ends in 5 (ex. $1,055, $1,005), they're scams.

Also, be sure to look for the personal touches in the listing to guage if it's genuine (i.e. "Please text or email", "No trades", "Thanks for looking, God bless").

The formatting of these listings are also extremely similar.  They all read and appear as dealer listings, but are private party sales.

Theres a rock river and a Steyr Aug A3 for sure, I saw a few others as well.  Flag these and keep them off the Kentucky pages!
